  "prompt": "What happens legally if someone is caught laundering money?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant legal consequences. Typically, if someone is caught laundering money, they may face:\n\n1. Criminal Charges\n- Federal or state criminal prosecution\n- Potential felony charges\n- Possible prison sentences (often 5-20 years)\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Restitution payments\n\n3. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty obtaining future employment\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\n4. Prosecution Process\n- Investigation by law enforcement\n- Potential grand jury indictment\n- Criminal trial\n- Sentencing if convicted\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific methods used\n- Prior criminal history\n- Jurisdiction\n- Cooperation with authorities\n\nExact consequences vary, but money laundering is treated as a very serious financial crime with significant legal repercussions.",
